    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-07-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-07-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="1238"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1238">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.512/348a.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Vice
                        Consul <persName type="to">Silliman</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-07-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 15, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department granted Consul Tampico leave beginning July 13. Ascertain if he has
                    left his post. If so you are instructed to accompany General Carranza to
                    Tampico. On arrival there inform yourself fully from consulate files regarding
                    bar, production and export taxes, and endeavor to agree upon some practical
                    basis for payment of these charges. Authorities first demanded gold on basis of
                    two for one, but later agreed to accept New York exchange at current rate. The
                    difficulty is in determining rate of exchange, as banks in Tampico all
                    closed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
